    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-22T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-22T22:00:00-05:00" n="251"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8934: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-23T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 23, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 23—9:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>323. 1. Hidaka told a foreign correspondent this morning that the Chinese were
                    very much mistaken if they thought the Japanese were bluffing in respect to the
                    sending of National Government troops in Hopei; the Japanese Government had made
                    three <hi rend="italic">démarches</hi> in this respect (Japanese Assistant
                    Military Attaché to Vice Minister of War July 17, Hidaka to Wang Chung Hui
                    midnight July 17, and Kita to Ho Ying Chin July 19) and these were not empty
                    gestures.</p>
                <p>2. We learn from reliable source that 10 cars of Chinese troops passed northward
                    yesterday through Hsuchowfu, Kiangsu, into Shantung.</p>
                <p>3. As far as known no official reports from foreign military observers in Japan
                    have been received here confirming the despatch from Japan of 35,000 troops
                    which are persistently reported in the press as having been scheduled to arrive
                    in Tangku yesterday or today.</p>
                <p>Sent to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
